{
  "texts": [
    "Thus, we can say that any practically rational agent is also a cognitive agent (if not vice versa).",
    "Practically rational agents are characterised be their being able to chunk and integrate information into networks of means-end beliefs that guide their behaviour.",
    "They thus manifest a kind of holism and consistency in what they do so that, for example, an agent who believes that it is raining and wants to avoid getting wet will bring an umbrella with her when she leaves the house -unless she has some other means to this end (e.g., she is wearing a hooded raincoat) or has some overriding reason to avoid doing so (e.g., the only available umbrella is a precious heirloom that might get damaged if she takes it out).",
    "At least typically, they can reflect on and give reasons for their behaviour, where these reasons presuppose general norms about how these more sophisticated cognitive faculties should bear on what the agent does (see and cf.",
    "Bacharach & Hurley 1991; Bermúdez, 2009)."
  ]
}